<subSubSection pageId="188" pageNumber="189" type="type">
<paragraph pageId="188" pageNumber="189">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="188" pageNumber="189">
Based on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wood &amp; Williams &amp; Mitchell &amp; Carine &amp; Harris &amp; Scotland" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus bushiricus" order="Solanales" pageId="188" pageNumber="189" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bushiricus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="188" pageNumber="189">Convolvulus bushiricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bornm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="188" pageNumber="189" type="distinguishing features">
<paragraph pageId="188" pageNumber="189">Distinguishing features.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="188" pageNumber="189">
Differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="subsp. cephalopodus" order="Solanales" pageId="188" pageNumber="189" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="bushiricus" subSpecies="cephalopodus">subsp. cephalopodus</taxonomicName>
in the longer, softer villous indumentum, the longer leaves (2.5-9 v. 1.5-4 cm) with less obviously undulate margins, the hairy style, in which the stigmas are longer than the united part, the lanceolate bracteoles and narrower sepals, the outer only 2-2.5 mm wide. The defining characters are not well differentiated and intermediates are known to occur. The ovary is hirsute, not glabrous as stated by Rechinger (1964: 486). [
<bibRefCitation author="Sa'ad, F" journalOrPublisher="Bronder Offset, Rotterdam" pageId="210" pageNumber="211" pagination="1 - 287" refId="B314" refString="Sa'ad, F, 1967. The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht. Bronder Offset, Rotterdam: 1 - 287" title="The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht" year="1967">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sa’ad">Sa'ad</normalizedToken>
1967
</bibRefCitation>
: 151; 
<bibRefCitation author="Collenette, S" journalOrPublisher="National Commission for Wildlife Conservation and Development, Riyadh" pageId="201" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 799" refId="B92" refString="Collenette, S, 1999. Wild flowers of Saudi Arabia. National Commission for Wildlife Conservation and Development, Riyadh: 1 - 799" title="Wild flowers of Saudi Arabia" year="1999">Collenette 1999</bibRefCitation>
: 228 (photo); 
<bibRefCitation author="Daoud, HS" journalOrPublisher="Kegan Paul Intenational, London" pageId="201" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 224" refId="B98" refString="Daoud, HS, Al-Rawi, A, 1985. Flora of Kuwait 1: Dicotyledonae. Kegan Paul Intenational, London: 1 - 224" title="Flora of Kuwait 1: Dicotyledonae" year="1985">Daoud and Al-Rawi 1985</bibRefCitation>
(Plates 215-217)]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="188" pageNumber="189" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="188" pageNumber="189">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="188" pageNumber="189">
Principally around the head of the Persian/Arabian Gulf: Iran (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="188" pageNumber="189">Kasy</emphasis>
356); Iraq (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="188" pageNumber="189">Rawi &amp; Rechinger</emphasis>
17242, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="188" pageNumber="189">Rechinger</emphasis>
8812); Kuwait (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="188" pageNumber="189">Dickson</emphasis>
60, 748, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="188" pageNumber="189">Rawi et al.</emphasis>
10521); Saudi Arabia (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="188" pageNumber="189">Holm</emphasis>
60, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="188" pageNumber="189">Mandaville</emphasis>
552, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="188" pageNumber="189">Collenette</emphasis>
2497, 9406).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="188" pageNumber="189" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="188" pageNumber="189">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="188" pageNumber="189">
<bibRefCitation author="Mandaville, JP" journalOrPublisher="Kegan Paul International Ltd., London and New York" pageId="207" pageNumber="208" pagination="1 - 482" refId="B222" refString="Mandaville, JP, 1990. Flora of eastern Saudi Arabia. Kegan Paul International Ltd., London and New York: 1 - 482" title="Flora of eastern Saudi Arabia" year="1990">Mandaville (1990</bibRefCitation>
: 246) suggests that the distinguishing features of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="subsp. bushiricus" order="Solanales" pageId="188" pageNumber="189" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="bushiricus" subSpecies="bushiricus">subsp. bushiricus</taxonomicName>
may be the result of seasonal or edaphic factors. This seems unlikely in the case of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boiss., Diagn. Pl. Orient. 7: 24. 1846. (Boissier" authorityYear="1846" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus cephalopodus" order="Solanales" pageId="188" pageNumber="189" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cephalopodus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="188" pageNumber="189">Convolvulus cephalopodus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as only material from around the head of the Gulf seems to conform to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Wood &amp; Williams &amp; Mitchell &amp; Carine &amp; Harris &amp; Scotland" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="subsp. bushiricus" order="Solanales" pageId="188" pageNumber="189" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="cephalopodus" subSpecies="bushiricus">subsp. bushiricus</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="188" pageNumber="189">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bornm., Beih. Bot. Centralbl. 20 (2): 181. 1906. (Bornmueller" authorityYear="1906" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus euphraticus" order="Solanales" pageId="188" pageNumber="189" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="euphraticus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="188" pageNumber="189">Convolvulus euphraticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar morphogically but has consistently larger heads c. 2.5 cm in diameter as opposed to 1.5 cm in diameter in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Wood &amp; Williams &amp; Mitchell &amp; Carine &amp; Harris &amp; Scotland" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus cephalopodus subsp. bushiricus" order="Solanales" pageId="188" pageNumber="189" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="cephalopodus" subSpecies="bushiricus">Convolvulus cephalopodus subsp. bushiricus</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
